2ND PHASE OF CLEANUP After Linux Kernel 7.0.4.02 

error: implicit declaration of function ‘setup_timer’ [-Wimplicit-function-declaration]
2904 |         setup_timer(&dev->sustain_timer, sustain_timer_clb, nr);

The error implicit declaration of function ‘setup_timer’ confirms that the version of v4l2loopback you are trying to compile is incompatible with kernel 7.0.4.

In Linux kernel 6.15 and later (including your 7.0.4 version), the old setup_timer() function was completely removed. It was deprecated years ago and replaced by timer_setup(). The source code currently on your system (likely version 0.12.7 or older from the Debian repo) still uses the old function, causing the compilation to fail.

Solution: Use the latest code from GitHub

The maintainers have already fixed this in the most recent versions of the code. You must compile from the latest source rather than the outdated Debian package.

Run these commands to fetch the fixed version and compile it:

bash

# 1. Remove the failed/broken attempt if it exists
sudo dkms remove v4l2loopback --all 2>/dev/null
sudo apt-get remove v4l2loopback-dkms -y

# 2. Ensure headers and build tools are installed
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y dkms build-essential linux-headers-$(uname -r) git

# 3. Clone the latest repository (which contains the timer_setup() fix)
git clone https://github.com/umlaeute/v4l2loopback.git
cd v4l2loopback

# 4. Clean any previous build artifacts and compile
make clean
make

# 5. Install the module
sudo make install

# 6. Load the module
sudo modprobe v4l2loopback                 

